Day 1 — Linux Core Setup, SSH & Static IP

Portfolio Artifact Name: Phase1_Day1_CoreSetup

1️⃣ Lab Metadata
Lab Name: Day 1 — Linux Core Setup, SSH & Static IP
Phase: Phase 1 – Core Systems
Objective: Provision a Linux VM with a static IP, secure SSH, basic firewall, and baseline networking.
Disciplines Covered: Linux Systems, Networking, DevOps Foundation
Roles Enabled: Linux SysAdmin, Junior DevOps Engineer, DevOps Engineer
Estimated Duration: 2–3 hours
Dependencies: None
Lab Version: 1.1
Date: 2026-02-07
2️⃣ Lab Overview / Consulting Context

Every enterprise system starts with a solid OS foundation and predictable networking. A static IP ensures consistent SSH access and reliable multi-node communication. This lab sets the groundwork for on-prem hybrid architecture and SRE-ready operations.

3️⃣ Prerequisites

Host machine (local or cloud VM)

Ubuntu 22.04 LTS ISO or prebuilt VM

Terminal / SSH client

Basic Linux command knowledge

4️⃣ Step-by-Step Lab Execution (With Objectives)
Step 1 — VM Creation

Objective: Provision a Linux VM to serve as the foundational node for on-prem/hybrid experiments.

# Vagrantfile example
Vagrant.configure("2") do |config|
  config.vm.box = "ubuntu/bionic64"
  config.vm.hostname = "fsie-node1"
  # Assign a static private IP for consistent access
  config.vm.network "private_network", ip: "192.168.56.10"
  config.vm.provider "virtualbox" do |vb|
    vb.memory = "2048"
    vb.cpus = 2
  end
end
Step 2 — SSH Key Setup

Objective: Enable secure passwordless login to VM, mimicking enterprise SSH access.

# Generate SSH key pair on host
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "fsie-lab-key"

# Copy public key to VM
ssh-copy-id vagrant@192.168.56.10

# Test SSH login
ssh vagrant@192.168.56.10
Step 3 — Update OS & Install Core Packages

Objective: Ensure the VM has latest security patches and essential tools for automation and monitoring.

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y vim git curl ufw htop net-tools
Step 4 — Configure Hostname & Hosts

Objective: Establish a consistent hostname and local DNS resolution for multi-node labs.

sudo hostnamectl set-hostname fsie-node1
echo "192.168.56.10 fsie-node1" | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts
Step 5 — Configure Static IP Verification

Objective: Ensure VM maintains the static IP, enabling reliable multi-node network design later.

ip addr show
ping -c 3 192.168.56.10
Step 6 — Basic Firewall Configuration

Objective: Implement baseline network security and allow only required services.

sudo ufw default deny incoming    # Deny all incoming traffic by default
sudo ufw default allow outgoing   # Allow all outgoing traffic
sudo ufw allow ssh                # Allow SSH connections
sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw status verbose
Step 7 — Enable Time Synchronization

Objective: Keep server clock accurate for logging, monitoring, and hybrid/cloud coordination.

sudo timedatectl set-ntp true
timedatectl status
Step 8 — Verify Connectivity

Objective: Confirm network, DNS, and SSH setup is correct.

ping -c 3 8.8.8.8      # Internet connectivity
ping -c 3 google.com   # DNS resolution
ssh localhost          # Local SSH test
5️⃣ Automation Scripts / Config Files

VM_Setup.sh
Automates package installation & firewall configuration

#!/bin/bash
# Update system
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
# Install core tools
sudo apt install -y vim git curl ufw htop net-tools
# Firewall setup
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing
sudo ufw allow ssh
sudo ufw enable

SSH_Config.md → Documents SSH key setup, key location, permissions

Hosts_Config.md → Baseline hosts file & hostname configuration

6️⃣ Failure Injection & Observability

Scenario 1: SSH fails due to wrong key
Scenario 2: Firewall blocks SSH access
Scenario 3: Static IP conflicts or misconfiguration

Artifacts:

FailureInjection.txt → steps & observations

FailureInjection.png → screenshots/logs

